                      <div align="center">
                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%" bgcolor="#004242">
                              <p align="center" style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><b><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#FFFFFF">DESCRIPTION</font></b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">
For those of you that read my first zone guide:  The Field of Bone, this zone guide will run fairly the same.  We'll go over what levels should be fought, how many in the group, landmarks and the like.  All in all the main focus of my guides is that you make it through the zone as quickly as possible.  I don't concentrate on quests because there are only a few that yield anything other than items for your level range, simply put: they yield little experience.  
<br><br>
For starters, the Lake of Ill Omen (LoIO) is a massive zone, easily comparable to the largest of the Karanas.  And just like the Field of Bone, this is a GREAT place to level.  It IS possible to start at level one here, but honestly I'd wait until your 20th+ level to venture out this far.  The reasoning is that mobs for the lower levels spread far apart and nowhere near any logical zone.  are However starting as early as your late teens, it's entirely possible to begin soloing or even grouping in this populated zone.  Populated you say?  Yes, the LoIO can generally have up to 100+ players at once due to it's capabilities to sustain levels from 1-30+.  Truthfully however, you'll want to leave this zone around 28 or 29 and head to the Frontier Mts. (where you can literally spend your next 10 levels.)  But for those of you that choose to take it slow, there is the ability to hang out at the lake for awhile.
<br><br>
When dealing with a zone as large as the LoIO it is essential to know and recognize landmarks, as well as have the map fairly memorized so that you can actually navigate with these landmarks.  The first landmarks are the ruined gates of Cabilis in the northeast corner.  As usual bind just inside this zone wall if your faction allows (faction should be dramatically adjusted in your favor [with the Legions of Cabilis/guards] if you followed my Field of Bone zone guide.)  Aside from binding, buying/selling/trading and corpse recoveries, you'll rarely pass through this end of the zone (this is assuming you're coming in at late teens, early twenties and up.)  Also this is the only area of the zone with support from the Legions of Cabilis, so if you're not near it you have nothing to fear from the Iksar people.  Next up is the lake itself.  Highly visible from almost most areas in the zone, it is also a great landmark.  In the middle of the lake is the Temple of Veksar zone.  Although the temple is not yet live, it helps you as a compass of sorts since there are two parallel columns running from it that point directly to the Frontier Mts. zone (keep in mind there is a mountain range in between the lake and the FM zone, so use the columns as a guide.)  The lake also has a small tributary that runs from he ocean in Firiona Vie.  Keeping this in mind, the small creek on the northwest edge of the lake will lead you directly to the Firiona Vie zone.  Both the FV (Firiona Vie) and FM (Frontier Mts.) zones serve as great alternatives when running from mobs since they are literally half as far away as the Cabilis gate.  In general you'll also find minor landmarks such as an undead structure, (charbones and warbones) three goblin ruins, and a couple of abandoned structures all surrounding the lake.  The major landmarks here are the Windmill, the Goblin Caves, and the Sarnak Fortress.  These landmarks will be covered in further detail in the coming sections.  Two notes I want to point out:  there is a fourth zone line which I will cover shortly; secondly, NEVER go into the lake.  There's a level 43+ Bloodgill Marauder (looks like a standard goblin warrior) that will rip you to shreds.  Specifically he hangs out at the base of the sunken Temple of Veksar, but he can get pulled out into the outer reaches of the lake fairly easily.  He will kill you.  With that behind us, let's talk about where to level in the Lake of Ill Omen.
<br><br>
When you first come in, you should either be high teens or already low 20's.  The most common is roughly 19-20.  If you feel this zone is too much for you, take a small group (2-3) back to the Field of Bone and take on the Iksar caves until 21 (at which point you'll be taking a serious exp. penalty for fighting lower levels.)  If you ARE ready, the first option is the Windmill.  Personally, I despise the Windmill.  Here you'll find the Professor who has an upper level quest.  Otherwise he serves no purpose and he WILL NOT save you if you try and run mobs to him.  The best place to run to is the FV zone, and if you've seen the map of this zone, that's quite a run.  My take on this camp is that it's generally heavily camped and the spawns are far apart.  Together that makes this camp a little too slow for me.  If you do decide to use the Windmill, SOW is almost essential for the pull.  As I was saying, the mobs are far apart and the most common pulling area is the undead building which is fairly far from the actual Windmill.  Common pulls are icebones, charbones, warbones, sabertooths and the like.  Sarnak generally stay behind the windmill toward the main goblin ruins.  The loot here isn't all that fantastic either.  Generally no drop quest items can be found with little or no cash.  Sabertooth teeth sell for 1pp as a note.  Spend 15 minutes here, and you'll see why it's on my least popular list.
<br><br>
Another common mistake in the lake is to camp the goblin ruins or the beaches nearby.  My advice: If you do it, do it with a group (I know that was a mouthful.)  Generally the goblins spawn in pairs in separate rooms, but it is possible to accidentally pull the entire camp if the wrong goblin is attacked.  Even with a full group, you will die.  For this reason, I suggest that if you're going to pull stand near the grouped columns near the main goblin ruins, and pull wandering constructs and sabertooths.  When you hit 22 however, move to the next major landmark: the Goblin Caves.
<br><br>
At 22, moving to the Goblin Caves is a great idea.  There are two entrances to the windy caverns and the more subtle one (the one without posted guards in the side of the mountain, the further east location) is my entrance of choice.  It may not be closer to the zone, but if you need to run from the caves, there aren't two guards waiting for you on the way out (sometimes however there may be a wanderer, one is still less than two though.)  Using this entrance to the cave, if you take three consecutive rights upon entering you will zone into Warsliks Woods (this is the fourth zone line I mentioned earlier.)  I would start with a packed group, a monk is almost essential at this point because Lord Gorelik is a wandering level 40+ mob (he drops the Mithril Staff, one of two great class specific drops in this zone) and the puller will get mopped up unless they manage to feign death.  The preferred pulling spot is just inside the tunnels at the first crossroad (there's a wooden bench at the cross.)  Two reasons: Should things get out of hand and running is the only option, then it's fairly simple to leave the cave directly without getting lost; secondly, the puller has two different pathways to pull from and hence has more options.  This area can turn into a perma-pull (new phrase.)  Perma-pulls in my mind are where the puller, if capable with good timing, can consistently pull mobs so that there is hardly ever any downtime.  A good example would be to leave the fight when the mob is 3/4's dead so that they are on their way to another mob, yet they are still close enough for exp gain.  This sweet spot in the Goblin Caves can serve you well into lvl 25, possibly even 26.  Another bonus is that after all this fighting, you'll get a great Firiona Vie faction hit.  Every goblin increases that faction, and for some, this opens up a new pathway off of Kunark.
<br><br>
The Goblin Caves are a great example of how well this zone is set up.  But the Sarnak Fortress is hands down a fantastic place for experience gain.  Once you're into the upper-mid 20s, you MUST head to the Sarnak Fortress.  There are two entrances to this place just like there were with the Goblin Caves.  However this time you'll want to head to the main entrance.  The main entrance is the one farther south, and it has two ways of entrance.  First is near the Sarnak Bridge next to the first tower (you can see this perfectly from the Frontier Mountain zone.)  Using this you can cross the bridge, which is sometimes guarded, and take your group down the pathway to what is commonly referred to as the hill (and we'll discuss the hill more in just a moment.)  The second entrance is the main gate, two side by side towers with an unmistakable entryway.  The open grass in front of the main gate is a fantastic place to pull if you don't want to go into the nest, although it could end up being relatively slower.  If you have a good group of people from level 23-29, (the closer in level the better) you should take the hill.  Conveniently located to the right of the entrance inside the Sarnak Fortress walls.  The hill is essentially a spot, that when the group stands far enough up on it, is devoid of accidental roamers.  From here the group has a view of the entire inner gate area, and simple spell casting can be used to effectively pull, while not putting the puller in danger.  This is another perma-pull spot.  The puller has complete control over everything in view.  Only small trips need to be made if the spawn run out in the temple.  What's more, if the group is confident, (experienced with their class, and roughly 27+ apiece) it is possible to retire from the hill and head into the first crossroad in the fortress interior.  One reason to do this, is the Sarnak Fortress is fairly popular, and the spawns may be taken out as they appear.  However, the fortress interior is usually devoid of competition so spawns can be increased with a good puller.  The only thing to fear, unless you're headed here as an upper level candidate, is getting closer to the throne room.  Sarnak Revenants can fear, and generally send you screaming deeper into the Fortress, and at that point, you've got quite a few Sarnak to handle.  It's best just to stay near the front at that first crossroad I mentioned.  If you are an upper level candidate (40+ with group) the Jade Chokidai Prod is in here on the Chancellor.  Head towards the throne room (the way there is naturally progressive, take a look at the maps) and clean your way into the final destination.
<br><br>
All in all, this zone is much like the FoB in that it's designed with a very specific system for getting through the 20's with rapidity.  Once again I remind you that these are strategies that are mapped out in a streamlined fashion, ensuring the quickest route to level 30.  Stay tuned for the Frontier Mts. guide which I will be wrapping up shortly.
<br><br>
<b>Extras</b>
<br><br>
The LoIO is definitely a zone in which you can get lost easily.  With this in mind, have a sense direction skill hot keyed so you can continually tap it.  Usually within the first 5 minutes of a new level, you'll improve all 5 skill points, and not have to repeat the process until your next ding.
                           </font></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%" bgcolor="#004242">
                              <p align="center" style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><b><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#FFFFFF">COMMENTS</font></b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
<tr><td width="100%"><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#004242"><b>GUIDE TO THE LAKE</font><font size="2" face="Tahoma"></b> - by <b>DaEbola</b> on 1/17/01</font></td></tr><tr><td width="100%"><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">This zone is excellent for players looking for fun in the outdoors and endless mobs to kill. Its very diverse for the level of mobs, ranging from level 1 goblins and critters roaming outside Cabilis, to level 35+ Bloodgill goblins roaming at the bottom of the lake. The lake is definitely a vast area to explore with plenty of scenery. The Lake of Ill Omen connects to 4 different zones: Firiona Vie (1250, -4375), West Cabilis (6400, -6700), Warslik Woods (4330, 1150) & Frontier Mountains (-250, 3350).
<br><br>
When starting in the lower levels (1-10), most will have no trouble finding monsters within reach at Northeast part of zone, outside West Cabilis. As the zone is very diverse, monsters will be spread out, getting tougher as you venture further from Cabilis. Upon reaching higher levels (15-20), two great spots to camp are the goblin camps located by the lake. One at north end (-175, 900), and other at east side of lake (-450, -1450). The goblins located in these ruins have a tendency to agro when you pull because they're close together, to be sure to lull/harmony once in awhile.
<br><br>
When advancing to levels (21-25), a great place to move on to are the goblin caves (entrance at: 3350, 1785). Goblins are spread out and tunnels seem long for first-timers. With an organized group, camping out in a room and having a pulling is fairly simple. Just be careful to avoid Lord Gorelik, this goblin is a TOUGH shaman even for level 20+ groups to handle.
<br><br>
For higher level characters (25-30), I strongly recommend the sarnak fortress in Southwest part of the zone (-3000, 2600). Most groups tend to camp outside entrance, and pull sarnaks out. This has proven to be great XP. in my personal experience when you pull from fort and grab roaming mobs from outside the fort (IE Goblin Warlords, Sabretooths, Charbone skeletons). And when the fortress gets overcrowded outside, groups can move into the fort tunnels and find it fairly safe with an organized group. Be wary though, in back of the fortress, rests Chancellor of Di'Zok. He rests on throne in a big dining hall. Hes a level 40 shaman, and drops Jaded Chokidai Prod for Charasis key quest.
<br><br>
For groups seeking a change of pace from normal hunting, there are bloodgill goblins resting at bottom of lake, ranging from level 35-40. Its usually good to fix a group on shore, have 1 puller dive in with Spirit of Wolf, and pull goblins to surface. And be careful doing this, most times the goblins comes in pairs, rarely able to pull them 1 at a time. If by any chance you kill a Bloodgill Marauder and an no drop amulet drops, let it be known that its for Veeshan's Peak key quest.</font></td></tr>
